><DIV
CLASS="QANDADIV"
><H3
><A
NAME="AEN241"
></A
>1. Updating the <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>FAQ</ACRONYM
></H3
><DIV
CLASS="QANDAENTRY"
><DIV
CLASS="QUESTION"
><P
><A
NAME="Q-META-UPDATE"
></A
><B
>1.1.1. </B
>Where can I get a new version of this document?</P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="ANSWER"
><P
><B
> </B
>The following procedure, developed for the <SPAN
CLASS="PRODUCTNAME"
>UNIX</SPAN
> operating
system, should provide you with the current version of this document:</P
><DIV
CLASS="PROCEDURE"
><OL
TYPE="1"
><LI
CLASS="STEP"
><P
>Make sure you have a working version of
<ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>CVS</ACRONYM
> for your operating system, and that you can make
connections to the <SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>Internet</SPAN
></SPAN
>.</P
><OL
CLASS="SUBSTEPS"
TYPE="a"
><LI
CLASS="STEP"
><P
>If you are going to update an existing version,
you may directly jump to <A
HREF="NTP-a-faq.htm#FAQ-STEP-CVS-UPDATE"
>step 5</A
>.</P
></LI
></OL
></LI
><LI
CLASS="STEP"
><P
>For convenience let's set a variable in the shell
using either <KBD
CLASS="USERINPUT"
>set
FAQREPO=:pserver:anoncvs@www.ntp.org:/cvs/ntp</KBD
> for the C shell, or
<KBD
CLASS="USERINPUT"
>FAQREPO=:pserver:anoncvs@www.ntp.org:/cvs/ntp</KBD
> for
<ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>POSIX</ACRONYM
> compatible shells.</P
></LI
><LI
CLASS="STEP"
><P
>Log in to the <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>NTP</ACRONYM
> repository using
<KBD
CLASS="USERINPUT"
>cvs -d $FAQREPO login</KBD
>.  The password is
<TT
CLASS="LITERAL"
>anoncvs</TT
>.  This will allow further commands.</P
></LI
><LI
CLASS="STEP"
><P
>Create a subdirectory with all the files using
<KBD
CLASS="USERINPUT"
>cvs -d $FAQREPO checkout ntpfaq</KBD
>.  Please consult the
documentation on <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>CVS</ACRONYM
> for details and available
options.</P
></LI
><LI
CLASS="STEP"
><A
NAME="FAQ-STEP-CVS-UPDATE"
></A
><P
>To save time and bandwidth when updating, simply
change to the directory containing the <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>FAQ</ACRONYM
> and type <KBD
CLASS="USERINPUT"
>cvs
update</KBD
>.  That command will update your files according to the
repository.</P
></LI
></OL
></DIV
><P
>An online version should be available at <A
HREF="http://www.ntp.org/ntpfaq/"
TARGET="_top"
><TT
CLASS="LITERAL"
>http://www.ntp.org/ntpfaq/</TT
></A
>.  The
current top-level file is <TT
CLASS="FILENAME"
>NTP-a-faq.htm</TT
>.<A
NAME="FTN-VOLATILE-URL"
HREF="#FTN.FTN-VOLATILE-URL"
><SPAN
CLASS="footnote"
>[1]</SPAN
></A
></P
><P
>Please note that checking out the <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>CVS</ACRONYM
>
sources will provide the <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>SGML</ACRONYM
> sources as well as the <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>HTML</ACRONYM
>
pages.  I cannot make a statement about what will be available via
<ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>HTTP</ACRONYM
>, but I expect that only the <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>HTML</ACRONYM
> files are there, and
listing the directory will not work.</P
></DIV
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="QANDAENTRY"
><DIV
CLASS="QUESTION"
><P
><A
NAME="AEN292"
></A
><B
>1.1.2. </B
>When will a new version of this document be
available?</P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="ANSWER"
><P
><B
> </B
>I edit this document in my spare time.  My spare time is
quite rare.  Therefore I rely on contributions to improve this work (see <A
HREF="NTP-a-faq.htm#Q-HOWTO-CONTRIBUTE"
>Q: 1.4.2.</A
>).  Feel free to contact me if you want to make a
contribution.</P
><P
>I hope to update this document as soon as important new stuff
is available.  The same applies for severe bug fixes.</P
></DIV
></DIV
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="QANDADIV"
><H3
><A
NAME="D-META-NAMING"
></A
>2. Naming</H3
><DIV
CLASS="QANDAENTRY"
><DIV
CLASS="QUESTION"
><P
><A
NAME="AEN301"
></A
><B
>1.2.1. </B
>Why is this Document named <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>FAQ</ACRONYM
>?</P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="ANSWER"
><P
><B
> </B
>This document tries to answer <SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>frequently asked
questions</SPAN
></SPAN
> (<ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>FAQ</ACRONYM
>s) that can not (at least virtually) be answered
easily from the standard documentation.</P
></DIV
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="QANDAENTRY"
><DIV
CLASS="QUESTION"
><P
><A
NAME="AEN309"
></A
><B
>1.2.2. </B
>Why is this Document named
<SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>HOWTO</SPAN
></SPAN
>?</P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="ANSWER"
><P
><B
> </B
>In addition to just answering questions that users had, this
document also tries to give a gentle introduction and guidelines to the
newcomer.  The authors believe that it's better to use <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>NTP</ACRONYM
> correctly right
from the start rather than fixing all the problems after they occur.</P
><P
><SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>Gentle</SPAN
></SPAN
> in the paragraph above means
<SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>not too technical</SPAN
></SPAN
> and <SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>not too theoretical</SPAN
></SPAN
>.
However some basic, non-trivial understanding of real-life is required at
several points, so please accept these deviations from the goal.</P
></DIV
></DIV
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="QANDADIV"
><H3
><A
NAME="D-META-POLICY"
></A
>3. Policies</H3
><DIV
CLASS="QANDAENTRY"
><DIV
CLASS="QUESTION"
><P
><A
NAME="AEN322"
></A
><B
>1.3.1. </B
>Why can't I find information about ... in this
<ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>FAQ</ACRONYM
>?</P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="ANSWER"
><P
><B
> </B
>Unless it simply has not been written yet, there may be other
reasons:</P
><P
></P
><OL
TYPE="1"
><LI
><P
>The editors don't want to copy documentation that is
publicly available already.  This is especially true for standards,
specifications and manuals.  The editors think that referring is better than
copying.  The intention is to avoid redundancy while saving labour at the same
time.</P
></LI
><LI
><P
>Either the problem or the solution is too vague to
document it.  This is true for very special configurations that are not at all
common.  After all, we want to answer <SPAN
CLASS="emphasis"
><I
CLASS="EMPHASIS"
>frequently</I
></SPAN
> asked
questions here.</P
></LI
></OL
></DIV
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="QANDAENTRY"
><DIV
CLASS="QUESTION"
><P
><A
NAME="AEN334"
></A
><B
>1.3.2. </B
>Where should a new Entry be put?</P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="ANSWER"
><P
><B
> </B
>The answer to this question is quite delicate!  The
guidelines are probably these:</P
><P
></P
><UL
><LI
><P
>Try to understand the existing structure of the
document.</P
></LI
><LI
><P
>If there are similar entries there already, see where
the new one fits best.  Usually it's right near the existing one, or in a
corresponding section.  Possibly it makes sense to create a new section or
division.</P
></LI
></UL
></DIV
></DIV
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="QANDADIV"
><H3
><A
NAME="D-META-CONTRIB"
></A
>4. Making Contributions</H3
><DIV
CLASS="QANDAENTRY"
><DIV
CLASS="QUESTION"
><P
><A
NAME="AEN346"
></A
><B
>1.4.1. </B
>Why should I contribute?</P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="ANSWER"
><P
><B
> </B
>In <SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>the good old times</SPAN
></SPAN
> the <SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>Internet</SPAN
></SPAN
> was a
valuable source of information, and people were happy to share their
knowledge.  These days, however, people think of <SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>E-Commerce</SPAN
></SPAN
>,
how to make money.</P
><P
>I started writing this <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>FAQ</ACRONYM
> not to make money, but to have a
reference to refer to.  Thus I hope I'll be able to provide the needed
information to more people more quickly.  Unfortunately I do not know
everything.  So if you have solved some problem that may be of interest to
other people as well, please share your experience.</P
></DIV
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="QANDAENTRY"
><DIV
CLASS="QUESTION"
><P
><A
NAME="Q-HOWTO-CONTRIBUTE"
></A
><B
>1.4.2. </B
>How can I contribute?</P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="ANSWER"
><P
><B
> </B
>Contributions are very much appreciated.  Depending on your
possibilities you can:</P
><P
></P
><OL
TYPE="1"
><LI
><P
>Tell me about some error or incomplete information given.
I call it a <SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>minor contribution</SPAN
></SPAN
>.  If you want to be listed in
the hall of fame (also called <SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>credits</SPAN
></SPAN
>), just tell me when
contributing.  If you prefer anonymous contributions, they are welcome just the
same.</P
></LI
><LI
><P
>You can suggest an addition consisting of a question
together with its answer.  I call this a <SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>major contribution</SPAN
></SPAN
>.
Major contributions are definitely worth being listed as
<SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>author</SPAN
></SPAN
> in the header of the document if you like.  Of course
you can <SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>downgrade</SPAN
></SPAN
> your contribution to plain
<SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>credits</SPAN
></SPAN
> or nothing if you prefer.</P
><P
>Contributions are accepted in any format, but I prefer
plain <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>US-ASCII</ACRONYM
> or <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>ISO-8859-1</ACRONYM
>.  If you can
avoid it, don't send files in some text processing format.</P
></LI
><LI
><P
>Supplying a valid patch against the source of this
document will make the most appreciated contribution.  This allows you to be
listed as <SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>co-author</SPAN
></SPAN
>.  As before, you can downgrade your
contribution as you like.  For details see <A
HREF="NTP-a-faq.htm#Q-FAQ-SOURCE"
><I
><I
>In what format should I send contributions?</I
></I
></A
>.</P
></LI
></OL
></DIV
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="QANDAENTRY"
><DIV
CLASS="QUESTION"
><P
><A
NAME="Q-FAQ-SOURCE"
></A
><B
>1.4.3. </B
>In what format should I send contributions?</P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="ANSWER"
><P
><B
> </B
>This document is most likely not written in the format you
are seeing.  The document source is written in <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>SGML</ACRONYM
>
(<SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>Structure Generalized Markup Language</SPAN
></SPAN
>,
<ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>ISO-8879</ACRONYM
>) using the <SPAN
CLASS="PRODUCTNAME"
>DocBook</SPAN
>
<ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>DTD</ACRONYM
> (<SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>Document Type Definition</SPAN
></SPAN
>).  Therefore
the source document has a rather fixed structure, much unlike <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>HTML</ACRONYM
>.  See also
<A
HREF="NTP-a-faq.htm#Q-WHY-DOCBOOK"
>Q: 1.4.6.</A
>.</P
><P
>So the essence is: Try to learn writing documents conforming
to the DocBook <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>DTD</ACRONYM
>.  In the meantime I'll do my best
converting your input to the proper format (See the more general discussion in
<A
HREF="NTP-a-faq.htm#Q-HOWTO-CONTRIBUTE"
><I
><I
>How can I contribute?</I
></I
></A
>).</P
></DIV
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="QANDAENTRY"
><DIV
CLASS="QUESTION"
><P
><A
NAME="AEN395"
></A
><B
>1.4.4. </B
>Where should I send Contributions?</P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="ANSWER"
><P
><B
> </B
>The sources controlled by <SPAN
CLASS="PRODUCTNAME"
>CVS</SPAN
> can
be updated by various people, but contributions should be sent to the currently
defined editor.  Every <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>HTML</ACRONYM
> file contains a
<TT
CLASS="LITERAL"
>mailto:</TT
> hyperlink to the editor.  Many browsers allow
sending comments to the author that way.  Another method is to visit the file
<TT
CLASS="FILENAME"
>ChangeLog</TT
> found where the sources are (See <A
HREF="NTP-a-faq.htm#Q-META-UPDATE"
>Q: 1.1.1.</A
>).</P
></DIV
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="QANDAENTRY"
><DIV
CLASS="QUESTION"
><P
><A
NAME="AEN405"
></A
><B
>1.4.5. </B
>I contributed to this <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>FAQ</ACRONYM
>, but my name is not mentioned
anywhere.  What's wrong?</P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="ANSWER"
><P
><B
> </B
>Probably the fault of the editor.  Maybe he thought you don't
want to be listed, or he simply forgot.  <A
HREF="NTP-a-faq.htm#S-CREDITS"
>Section 1.1</A
> shows the
names the editor was aware of.</P
></DIV
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="QANDAENTRY"
><DIV
CLASS="QUESTION"
><P
><A
NAME="Q-WHY-DOCBOOK"
></A
><B
>1.4.6. </B
>Why <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>SGML</ACRONYM
> and
<SPAN
CLASS="PRODUCTNAME"
>DocBook</SPAN
>?</P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="ANSWER"
><P
><B
> </B
>Well, I'm not getting paid for my work, so I tried to learn
something new while writing this piece of documentation.
<ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>SGML</ACRONYM
> is one of the dinosaurs of information technology, an
endangered species that may be killed by the more agile
<ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>XML</ACRONYM
>.  So maybe feeding dinosaurs is just cool.</P
><P
><SPAN
CLASS="PRODUCTNAME"
>DocBook</SPAN
> is just another monster
that is used by even larger monsters like <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>HP</ACRONYM
> for
documentation.  Definitely it's also animal, because it's used by O'Reilly
&amp; Associates, Inc.<A
NAME="AEN423"
HREF="#FTN.AEN423"
><SPAN
CLASS="footnote"
>[2]</SPAN
></A
>
Finally it's an open technology: All specifications (and many tools) are freely
available.</P
><P
>Specific output formats are generated by applying
<SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>style sheets</SPAN
></SPAN
> within a framework consisting of <A
HREF="NTP-a-faq.htm#AU-JJC"
>James Clark</A
>'s <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>JADE</ACRONYM
> (<SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>James'
<ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>DSSSL</ACRONYM
> Engine</SPAN
></SPAN
>) and <A
HREF="NTP-a-faq.htm#AU-NDW"
>Norman Walsh</A
>'s
<SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>Modular DocBook Stylesheets</SPAN
></SPAN
>.  While this document probably
will be used mostly in <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>HTML</ACRONYM
> format, other formats like
<SPAN
CLASS="PRODUCTNAME"
>TeX</SPAN
> and <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>RTF</ACRONYM
> (<SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>Rich Text
Format</SPAN
></SPAN
>) can be generated as well.</P
></DIV
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="QANDAENTRY"
><DIV
CLASS="QUESTION"
><P
><A
NAME="AEN442"
></A
><B
>1.4.7. </B
>How can I process the <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>SGML</ACRONYM
> source file?</P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="ANSWER"
><P
><B
> </B
>I'm editing this document with the <SPAN
CLASS="SYSTEMITEM"
>Linux</SPAN
>/<ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>GNU</ACRONYM
> operating
system.  Most Linux distributions come with the required tools.  In my
distribution these tools are in the following packages:</P
><P
></P
><TABLE
BORDER="0"
><TBODY
><TR
><TD
><TT
CLASS="FILENAME"
>emacs</TT
> (<SPAN
CLASS="PRODUCTNAME"
>GNU
Emacs</SPAN
>, the editor)</TD
></TR
><TR
><TD
><TT
CLASS="FILENAME"
>docbook_4</TT
> (The DocBook
<ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>DTD</ACRONYM
> and related files)</TD
></TR
><TR
><TD
><TT
CLASS="FILENAME"
>docbook-dsssl-stylesheets</TT
> (The
modular style sheets for DocBook)</TD
></TR
><TR
><TD
><TT
CLASS="FILENAME"
>openjade</TT
> (OpenJade, the follow-up to
Jade by James Clark's <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>DSSSL</ACRONYM
>-Engine for
<ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>SGML</ACRONYM
> Documents)</TD
></TR
><TR
><TD
><TT
CLASS="FILENAME"
>opensp</TT
> (The OpenJade Group's
<ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>SGML</ACRONYM
> and <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>XML</ACRONYM
> Parsing Tools)</TD
></TR
><TR
><TD
><TT
CLASS="FILENAME"
>psgml</TT
> (Provides
<ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>SGML</ACRONYM
> knowledge for Emacs.  I would not survive without
that!)</TD
></TR
></TBODY
></TABLE
><P
></P
><P
>You might want to have a look at these packages as well:
<TT
CLASS="LITERAL"
>docbook-css-stylesheets</TT
>, <TT
CLASS="LITERAL"
>docbook-tdg</TT
> (DocBook: The Definitive
Guide)</P
><P
>So if you want to edit and validate any changes you are
making, try to get the equivalent tools for your operating system as well.  If
you like the pain, you can use these tools on <SPAN
CLASS="TRADEMARK"
>Microsoft
Windows</SPAN
>&#8482; as well.</P
><P
>Basically the command to generate <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>HTML</ACRONYM
> files is
<KBD
CLASS="USERINPUT"
>jade -t sgml -d NTP-FAQ.dsl#html NTP-FAQ.sgml</KBD
> where the
environment contains these special settings:</P
><PRE
CLASS="SCREEN"
>SGML_CATALOG_FILES=SGML_CATALOG_FILES=/var/lib/sgml/CATALOG.docbook_4
SGML_SEARCH_PATH=/usr/share/sgml/docbook/dsssl-stylesheets/html</PRE
></DIV
></DIV
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="QANDADIV"
><H3
><A
NAME="D-META-APPEARANCE"
></A
>5. Appearance</H3
><DIV
CLASS="QANDAENTRY"
><DIV
CLASS="QUESTION"
><P
><A
NAME="Q-META-CSS-STYLE"
></A
><B
>1.5.1. </B
>I don't like the look of the <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>FAQ</ACRONYM
>.  What can I
do?</P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="ANSWER"
><P
><B
> </B
>You are lucky: Actually the source of the <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>FAQ</ACRONYM
> uses no
formatting rules at all, even the <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>DSSSL</ACRONYM
> code relies on
<ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>HTML</ACRONYM
> classes and style sheets to do the rendering.  All properties like
borders, colours, and font attributes are taken from a <SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>cascading style
sheet</SPAN
></SPAN
> (<ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>CSS</ACRONYM
>).</P
><P
>In practice, this means you don't have to change the <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>HTML</ACRONYM
>
source to change the appearance.  Instead simply provide your favourite user
style sheet to do the formatting.  If you prefer no fancy attributes at all,
just empty the <TT
CLASS="FILENAME"
>docbook.css</TT
> file.<A
NAME="AEN497"
HREF="#FTN.AEN497"
><SPAN
CLASS="footnote"
>[3]</SPAN
></A
></P
><P
>If the output looks extraordinarily odd, you may have a
broken <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>HTML</ACRONYM
> browser.  See also <A
HREF="NTP-a-faq.htm#Q-WHICH-BROWSER"
>Q: 1.5.2.</A
>.</P
><P
>If you think colours are inconsistently chosen, please make a
suggestion for future improvement.  If you dislike single colours or
combinations thereof, please suggest a change.  Doing that job is more an art
than a science.</P
><P
>I'm aware that some elements are not rendered the best
possibly way.  As I don't waste much time (at least not even more time) with
rendering of elements, I strongly rely on <A
HREF="NTP-a-faq.htm#AU-NDW"
>Norman Walsh</A
>'s competence
in <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>JADE</ACRONYM
> programming.  I'm hoping that things will improve
over time.</P
><DIV
CLASS="EXAMPLE"
><A
NAME="AEN506"
></A
><P
><B
>Example 1. Style Sheet Entry</B
></P
><PRE
CLASS="SCREEN"
>*.ACRONYM { color: #5838d0 }</PRE
><P
>This entry causes all <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>HTML</ACRONYM
> elements with attribute
<TT
CLASS="LITERAL"
>class=ACRONYM</TT
> (i.e. all acronyms) to be output in a kind of
royal blue.  The example shown does not use official <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>WWW</ACRONYM
>
colours.  It's strongly recommended to use official colours for
portability.</P
></DIV
><P
>If your browser goes mad, and your vendor allows you to
report bugs, feel free to report the problems to them.  If you think I went
mad, feel free to tell me too ;-)</P
></DIV
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="QANDAENTRY"
><DIV
CLASS="QUESTION"
><P
><A
NAME="Q-WHICH-BROWSER"
></A
><B
>1.5.2. </B
>Which Browser is required to read this?</P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="ANSWER"
><P
><B
> </B
>This <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>FAQ</ACRONYM
> is intended to be read with the famous <SPAN
CLASS="QUOTE"
>"any
browser"</SPAN
>.  It means that standard <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>HTML</ACRONYM
> is used,
omitting any fancy extensions.  Still individual browsers may implement
different subsets of the standard.</P
><P
>I usually test the output using the following
browsers in <SPAN
CLASS="SYSTEMITEM"
>Linux</SPAN
> (roughly ordered by fanciness):</P
><P
></P
><TABLE
BORDER="0"
><TBODY
><TR
><TD
><SPAN
CLASS="PRODUCTNAME"
>Mozilla</SPAN
> (<A
HREF="http://www.mozilla.org/releases/"
TARGET="_top"
><TT
CLASS="LITERAL"
>http://www.mozilla.org/releases/</TT
></A
>)</TD
></TR
><TR
><TD
><SPAN
CLASS="PRODUCTNAME"
>Amaya</SPAN
></TD
></TR
><TR
><TD
><SPAN
CLASS="PRODUCTNAME"
>w3m</SPAN
> (text-oriented, supports
tables)</TD
></TR
><TR
><TD
><SPAN
CLASS="PRODUCTNAME"
>Emacs/W3</SPAN
> (text-oriented,
supports tables)</TD
></TR
><TR
><TD
><SPAN
CLASS="PRODUCTNAME"
>Lynx</SPAN
> (text-oriented,
<B
CLASS="COMMAND"
>vi</B
>-like)</TD
></TR
></TBODY
></TABLE
><P
></P
></DIV
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="QANDAENTRY"
><DIV
CLASS="QUESTION"
><P
><A
NAME="AEN539"
></A
><B
>1.5.3. </B
>Why are Graphics stored in <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>PNG</ACRONYM
>
Format?</P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="ANSWER"
><P
><B
> </B
>The popular <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>GIF</ACRONYM
> format supported by many
browsers relies on a compression algorithm that is patented, and the owner of
the patent wants to receive money from everyone making <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>GIF</ACRONYM
>
files.  <ACRONYM
CLASS="ACRONYM"
>PNG</ACRONYM
> (<SPAN
CLASS="phrase"
><SPAN
CLASS="PHRASE"
>Portable Network Graphics</SPAN
></SPAN
>)
uses a different algorithm for compression and does not require payment.</P
></DIV
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="QANDAENTRY"
><DIV
CLASS="QUESTION"
><P
><A
NAME="AEN549"
></A
><B
>1.5.4. </B
>Why are some Fonts that huge?</P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="ANSWER"
><P
><B
> </B
><SPAN
CLASS="PRODUCTNAME"
>Netscape Navigator</SPAN
> (e.g. version
4.74) seems to have a bug with relative font scaling.  Try to disable using
stylesheets, or try a recent <SPAN
CLASS="PRODUCTNAME"
>Mozilla</SPAN
>.  See also
<A
HREF="NTP-a-faq.htm#Q-META-CSS-STYLE"
>Q: 1.5.1.</A
>.</P
></DIV
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="QANDAENTRY"
><DIV
CLASS="QUESTION"
><P
><A
NAME="AEN557"
></A
><B
>1.5.5. </B
>Why are there no Frames?</P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="ANSWER"
><P
><B
> </B
>Sorry, I have my daily frustration with frames, so I don't
want any more.  Despite of that I think that most frames just consume valuable
space on either your screen or on your print-out.</P
></DIV
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="QANDAENTRY"
><DIV
CLASS="QUESTION"
><P
><A
NAME="AEN562"
></A
><B
>1.5.6. </B
>Why isn't there fancy Script Code?</P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="ANSWER"
><P
><B
> </B
>Currently scripting is neither fast nor portable, so I don't
use it.</P
></DIV
></DIV
></DIV
></DIV
